text:
Ambiance: very cold, literally; an antique-looking portable heater standing near the entrance didn't help at all; we had to dine with our winter coats on; very small space (seating max 25 people); as with most hipster places these days, very dim yellow light, good for concealing unwanted flaws if you're on a date; 

Service: polite, perhaps with a hint of snobbery, not particularly warm but adequate; for the sake of comparison, much prefer service at Kazu; wait time for most dishes were reasonable, albeit with a lot of patience; the ramen dish however took 20 minutes to arrive after the previous dish;

Food: do not be fooled by Facebook and blogger pictures; aside from the ramen, plates were tapas size, to be consumed in precisely 2 spoonfuls; we've sampled the hay-smoked beef carpaccio with arugula, chawanmushi (egg custard in a tea cup), grilled octopus, tuna tartare, chicken karrage (essentially deep fried high end organic chiken) and tonkotsu ramen; only the chicken somewhat stood out in flavour and texture: batter was crisp with notes of garlic and chili, meat was hot, moist and juicy; the rest were either tasteless (chawanmushi) or too salty (beef carpaccio) or ordinary (ramen included); quite overpriced for the quality and preparation; most ramen joints in Toronto would beat Iwashi, hands down; overall, nothing that we've tasted was memorable enough to inspire a second visit;
